## Does an "Ecologically Noble Savage" exist?

![](./1a_Alvard1993.png)

. . .

-   The premise of this manuscript is that the ecologically noble savage hypothesis may exist merely as a by-product of a misconception of what real conservation is

. . .

-   The effects of a certain behavior do not necessarily define the behavior itself

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Working hypotheses

-   $H_0$ = Native people are conservationists

    -   We expect native populations to adopt specific conservation behavior
    -   Hunting decisions are made to ensure sustainable harvests of prey
    -   Restrain has a short term cost outweighed by long term return

-   $H_1$ = Native people will over-exploit resources whenever it is to their advantage to do so

    -   Derived from foraging theory
    -   Hunters will over exploit resources whenever it is to their advantage to do so
    -   Short term rate-maximization of resources

. . .

The author sets up a quantitatively framework to directly and mathematically find support for either of the two alternative hypotheses. Specifically, the aim is to quantify how much the data he gathers in the field reflect the prediction regarding inter-specific prey choice.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

> ... the prey available to hunters vary in regard to vulnerability to overexploitation and local extinction, do their interspecific prey choices represent a conservation oriented decision? Or, do hunters choose prey that are optimal in terms of return rate maximization? Evidence for conservation would consist of hunters forgoing opportunities to kill vulnerable species that are nonetheless predicted by foraging theory to be pursued [@Alvard1993].

<br/>

> If indigenous people possess an intimate knowledge of their environment, it is not unreasonable to assume that native hunters are aware of the reproductive parameters and limitations of their prey species. Native hunters following a conservation strategy might be expected to use their knowledge to minimize their impact on their prey [@Alvard1993].

------------------------------------------------------------------------

![After @Alvard1993](./1b_Alvard1993.png)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

